Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. Defendant Terance Trent Williams in court with attorney Scott Paley Phillips.  Benjamin Lindsay appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Deputy court clerk cmt.
Defendant prepared to enter change of plea.  Hearing proceeded.  Negotiations set forth by the state.

The defendant was advised of hisr constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, plead GUILTY and was examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights, Addendum to Plea Questionnaire, and Jury Instructions received and filed.  The parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis for the plea.  The Court found the defendant guilty and ordered entry of Judgment of Conviction.  

Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by parties and defendant. 

Defendant ordered to serve 11 months in the House of Correction, credit of 232 days time served, and with Huber privileges for work and child care. Court stays report date to 12-26-2017 by 5:00 pm.
Defendant to pay DNA surcharge by 12-17-2018. Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment.
Court waives all other costs, fees and surcharges due to inability to pay. 
Pursuant to Wisconsin Statutes section 973.176, the Court advised the defendant of the following restrictions:  Firearm possession and Voting.
